109 Section 20 of this bill requires: (1) any using agency which uses the equipment
110 or services of the Office to adhere to the regulations, standards, practices, policies
111 and conventions of the Office; and (2) each using agency to report certain
112 information relating to certain suspected incidents to the Office of Information
113 Security and Cyber Defense and the Security Operations Center.
114 Existing law requires the Deputy Director of the Office of Information Security
115 and Cyber Defense to investigate and resolve any breach of an information system
116 of a state agency or elected officer that uses the equipment or services of the
117 Governor’s Technology Office. (NRS 242.183) Section 21 of this bill requires
118 instead that the Deputy Director, in consultation with the Security Operations
119 Center, investigate and resolve any breach of an information system of a using
120 agency.
121 Existing law authorizes the Governor to proclaim the existence of a state of
122 emergency or a declaration of disaster if the Governor in his or her proclamation
123 finds that certain events, including a technological or man-made emergency or
124 disaster of major proportions, have actually occurred in this State and that the
125 safety and welfare of the inhabitants of this State require such a proclamation.
126 (NRS 414.070) If the Governor has made such a proclamation concerning a critical
127 cybersecurity incident, section 21 authorizes the Governor to authorize the
128 information technology personnel of using agencies of the Executive Branch to
129 report directly to the Chief.
130 Existing law provides that the amount receivable from a state agency or officer
131 or local governmental agency which uses the services of the Governor’s
132 Technology Office must be determined by the Chief. (NRS 242.191) Section 22 of
133 this bill provides instead that the amount receivable from a using agency which
134 uses the services or equipment of the Office must be determined by the Chief.
135 Section 23 of this bill requires each using agency using the services or
136 equipment of the Office to pay a fee for such use to the Fund for Information
137 Services.
138 Section 24 of this bill makes an appropriation to the Office of Finance in the
139 Office of the Governor for the Governor’s Technology Office within the Office of
140 the Governor for investments related to cybersecurity. Section 24 additionally
141 encourages the Governor’s Technology Office to, in collaboration with other
142 agencies, apply for grants for investments related to cybersecurity and requires,
143 under certain circumstances, the Office to reserve for reversion to the State General
144 Fund the amount of money received from such a grant. Sections 25-27 of this bill
145 make appropriations to the Office of Finance in the Office of the Governor for a
146 loan to the Governor’s Technology Office within the Office of the Governor to
147 cover a shortfall in revenues for certain divisions and offices within the Governor’s
148 Technology Office.
